Bonus points: Kids eat FREE! A huge perk for families!

Its voted one of the most beautiful cinemas in the world. I loved the balcony seating and old fashioned feel of this cinema. Easy to book a ticket online for 17 dollars which seems average.

On arrival I showed my ticket on my phone, it was all very easy and the staff were very friendly, pleasant and welcoming.

A few negatives were that the bar doesn't open until the evening meaning afternoon movies can only be enjoyed with a soft drink. No big deal but would be nice if they had a small selection of alcoholic beverages available. But more disappointing was that you also couldn't get a hot drink. Just cold drinks and snacks.

You can take your own drinks in so I got a hot drink from a nearby cafe that was kindly recommended by the staff.

Also I found the cinema was too cold so I had to keep my coat on. Should be heated better on cold, wet days.

Despite the few points above I really enjoyed the film and my visit to this cinema. The staff are great and add to the whole experience.

People had mentioned uncomfortable seats but I found them to be completely comfortable, no recline but really comfortable still.

My.
Jebus.

I found Shanghainese Pork and Cabbage Noodle Soup on this side of the Hudson. And it's not only good....It's EXCELLENT!

Yes, yes, the dish by which all Shanghai restaurants are judged is XLBs. We didn't get them (*horrified gasps*). Instead, we ordered this noodle soup because it is my personal Shanghai culinary litmus test--and 62 SK passed with flying colors! The noodles were kiu kiu, the pork was buttery tender, the mustard greens were delightfully crunchy--and most important of all, the broth was an umami nirvana.

I'm going to throw hands: 62 Secret Kitchen's version surpasses Nan Xiang's, Din Tai Fung's and most of NYC's Shanghainese restaurants. It's that good.

Everything else we got was stellar too. The Fresh Chicken in Wine Sauce (AKA Drunken Chicken) was tender and succulent. The Shanghai Meatball with Salted Egg Yolk (AKA Lions Head) was perfectly braised, though a tad too sweet for my liking. And the savory Sauteed Blue Crab with Rice Cake was that perfect dish to ward off the lingering early spring evening chill.

Throw in the lovely modern yet traditional Chinese decor and friendly, attentive service (despite the place being packed), and you've got what's easily the best Chinese restaurant in downtown Jersey City. 10 years ago, a restaurant like this probably never would've survived in the area. Of course, grilled salmon is usually something that tastes good no matter where you go. I mean, you'd probably have to be a horrible cook to mess it up, but it wasn't just the salmon that was so good!

Usually, it's what goes along with your salmon that can make or break the entire meal. Most places just throw some hard, bad-tasting vegetables in to go along with it and hope you'll just be happy that the salmon tasted good!

But not this place! Not Angelo's! Everything was good! I actually stopped eating my salmon for a few so that I could spend time on the vegetables! That is not usually me! I'm usually not even a vegetable person because, usually, most places put garbage on your plate for vegetables. But these were very soft and the flavoring was superb!

Also, I usually eat things in order. For instance, I'll usually eat all of the salmon first, then move onto whatever is left. In this case, once I tried the vegetables, I had to keep going back and even stayed on them until I finished them all before finishing the salmon.

Everyone else's meals looked great as well! My wife especially liked her Pistachio Ravioli.

Make sure to give this place a try! It's located right near the Ed Sullivan Theater also. We came as a family outing but it was very undesirable, even the waiter? (Maybe?) And the same host wouldn't stop coming to the table like they were trying to hurry us to order to get in and out.

I won't be back to this location based on this experience. We ordered drinks and Duck Tacos to go because it was just not the welcoming vibe we were hoping for especially when we eat Dry Pot in Flushing all the time.

The Duck Tacos took a bit which is fine as I saw tons of Togo orders going by.  They tasted okay but they were also cold? My only intuition is they tried to westernize a Bao. So now I don't know why we waited so long for them.
